1H25 Earnings - In the, With NWC/FCF Unde Security
Unchanged Impact to our thesis
In-line Financial results versus consensus
Largely unchanged Direction of next 12-month consensus EPS
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research

EBIT is \(- 2\% +1\%\) vs. Va css/MSe. All three Contracting divisions outperform vs. small miss in other Concessions. The big NWC outflow as of June may come under scrutiny, although FCF was in line with MSe and holdco. net cash better. French politics take center stage for now, though.

In- line results: EBIT of €1,006m broadly in line \((- 2\% +1\%\) vs. VA css / MSe), NI of €308m bang in line with VA css / MSe. Contracting particularly solid, with a margin beat in all 3 segments (Construction, Infrastructure, Energy Systems) + good backlog across the board (esp. EES) Bigger NWC outflow than last year at - €892m + management guidance of likely small outflow at FY25e on fewer large projects bookings/prepayments a small negative Big picture, French political / tax uncertainties dominate vs. resilient fundamentals (in- line results, eye on NWC, progress on bolt- on M&A)
MORGAN STANLEY & CO. INTERNATIONAL PLC+
Eiffage SA (FOUG.PA, FGR FP)
Shr price, close (Aug 27, 2025)
Net debt (12/25e) (mn)

- €672m in 1H24 was put down to i) higher activity levels = mechanical larger seasonal outflow; ii) fewer large project wins = fewer prepayments booked. While the former should unwind into 2H25, in our view (collection measured in Days Sales Outstanding actually improved YoY in 1H25 by 5 days), fewer large projects expected to be signed into year-end should likely weigh on NWC for the year. As such, management pointed to a likely NWC unwind of up to \(\sim \epsilon 100m\) in FY25 (vs. MSe +€75m).

Valuation station: FGR stock is down 13% over 3 days following political uncertainty in France. The stock now trades on 10.6/10.1x 2025/26e P/E, 4.3%/4.5% dividend yield, \(\sim 12\%\) holdco. FCFE yield with a leverage of 2.0/1.8x 2025/26e ND/ EBITDA. Stripping out Eiffage Contracting on 7x 2025 EV/EBIT (30% discount to listed peers on high French political/tax uncertainty, conglomerate status, reinvestment risk), the Concessions stub trades on an implied 51% equity IRR.
Exhibit 1: Eiffage - Discount to MSe Fair Value
Source: Morgan Stanley Research estimates (e)

We use a SOTP splitting Concessions (DCF/DDM- based valuation) & Contracting (peers' multiples avg, given similar high exposure to relevant end markets) + apply a \(10\%\) holdco discount. APRR is valued on \(10\%\) CoE, \(1.0\%\) 2025- 36e traffic CAGR, with \(1.8\%\) LT French CPI; Contracting on \(9.5x\) 2025e EV/EBIT (Const 7x, Real Estate \(5.4x\) , Infrastructure \(7.1x\) , Energy Systems \(12x\) ). Getlink at market value, Toulouse Airport at \(\sim 80\%\) discount vs. purchase price
- European stimulus plans (German Infra; Defence)- Further strong order intake (esp. Infrastructure large projects)- Acceleration of bolt-on M&A strategy (Services / Infra / Concessions)
- French political/macro/fiscal uncertainty- Dislocation in yields impacting the valuation of Concessions- Regulatory risk (concessions' tax)- Lack of progress on reinvestment
